{
  "type": "feature",
  "title": "Parallelize summary + memory extraction in POST /api/conversation/end (PERF-HIGH)",
  "description": "Addresses the [PERF-HIGH] backlog item for conversation latency. Recent iterations parallelized /start (iter 625) and /message already runs grammar-check + reply via asyncio.gather. The remaining sequential bottleneck is POST /api/conversation/end in app/routers/conversation.py: it first awaits the conversation_summary LLM call (~6‚Äì10s) and then, before returning, performs a separate fact-extraction LLM call for cross-session memory (~3‚Äì6s). The user is blocked on the sum of both. Both calls only depend on `format_history_text(...)`, so they can run concurrently.\n\nChanges in `app/routers/conversation.py` `end_conversation`:\n1. When `req.skip_summary` is False, compute `history_text = await conv_dal.format_history_text(db, req.conversation_id)` ONCE (currently it's computed twice ‚Äî once for summary and once again for memory extraction; eliminate the duplicate read).\n2. Build two coroutines: `_summary_task()` wrapping the existing `safe_llm_call(... copilot.ask_json(conversation_summary)...)` with the same HTTPException ‚Üí fallback handling, and `_memory_task()` wrapping the existing fact-extraction `copilot.ask_json(...)` call (returns `[]` on any exception, never raises).\n3. `summary, new_facts = await asyncio.gather(_summary_task(), _memory_task())`.\n4. Keep the existing post-processing: `_normalize_summary`, attach metrics, `end_conversation(... summary=summary)`, and merge `new_facts` into `CONVERSATION_MEMORY_KEY` preference (dedupe case-insensitive, cap 10) ‚Äî same logic as today, just moved out of the try/except wrapper since the task itself swallows exceptions.\n5. When `skip_summary=True`, behavior is unchanged (no LLM calls, no memory extraction ‚Äî matches current code).\n6. Add an `info`-level log `\"end_conversation parallel LLM calls completed (%.1fs)\"` mirroring the pattern used in `/message` so latency is observable in logs.\n\nNo schema changes. No frontend changes (response shape identical). No config changes.\n\nExpected impact: end-of-conversation p50 latency cut from ~(T_summary + T_memory) to ~max(T_summary, T_memory), typically a 30‚Äì45% reduction on /end. Combined with prior /start and /message work this completes the asyncio.gather sub-task of the PERF-HIGH backlog item.\n\nTests to add in `tests/integration/test_conversation.py` (or the existing conversation integration test module ‚Äî reuse fakes already present for copilot):\n- `test_end_conversation_runs_summary_and_memory_in_parallel`: patch `get_copilot_service` so that `ask_json` returns a coroutine that records call start/end timestamps and sleeps ~0.2s. Start a conversation, send one message, call /end. Assert (a) both prompts (summary prompt containing 'Conversation' and the fact-extraction prompt containing 'extract 2-3 personal facts') were invoked, (b) their execution intervals overlap (max(start_b, start_a) < min(end_a, end_b)), and (c) total wall time < 1.5 * single-call duration.\n- `test_end_conversation_memory_failure_does_not_block_summary`: fake copilot where the memory-extraction call raises but summary succeeds ‚Üí response still 200 with valid summary; preferences row for `conversation_memory` remains unchanged.\n- `test_end_conversation_skip_summary_makes_no_llm_calls`: assert `ask_json` call count == 0 when `skip_summary=True`.\n- `test_end_conversation_history_text_computed_once`: spy on `conv_dal.format_history_text` and assert it is called exactly once during /end (regression guard for the dedup).\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n1. `pytest tests/integration -k end_conversation` passes including the four new tests.\n2. Existing conversation tests still pass (no behavioral regressions on response shape, status codes, or memory merging logic).\n3. With a fake copilot that sleeps 200 ms per call, /end completes in < 350 ms (proving parallelism), vs ~400 ms+ previously.\n4. `format_history_text` is invoked exactly once per /end request when `skip_summary=False`.\n5. `ruff check` and `mypy` (if configured) report no new issues in the modified file.",
